                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1784" notAfter="1785">
                        <p>Probably rebound in Britain, possibly for subsequent owner <persName
                              role="fmo ato ins" key="person_f3620">Samuel Hawtayne
                           Lewin</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Sewn on three raise cords, with endpapers of British-made laid paper with
                           ~8 laid lines per cm and ~28 mm between chain lines, applied over the
                           right flyleaves that commence the volume, but added as a folio
                           surrrounding the left flyleaves, evidently to reattach them after
                           becoming loose. Laced into pasteboards, edges trimmed and coloured bright
                           yellow, with single-core decorative front-bead endbands sewn at <locus
                              from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail"
                              >tail</locus>. Boards covered in full reverse calfskin
                              <material>leather</material>.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Twisted impressions by the spine bands reflect the
                           binder tying up the volume in a lying press, not hand-tooling. The second
                           panel down bears the title <q xml:lang="en">UPANISHAD</q> paletted in
                           gold.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>232</height>
                              <width>204</width>
                              <depth>50</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair, but stable condition, with
                           abrasion to the exterior, bumped lower corners, and broken
                           tailcap.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
