               <history>
                  <origin>Completed for <persName role="pat ins fmo" key="person_102326800"
                        ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/102326800/">Sir William Jones</persName> in
                        <origPlace ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001561" key="place_7001561"
                        >Lucknow</origPlace> undated, but <origDate cert="high"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1784" notAfter="1785-05-03">before 3 May
                        1785</origDate>, when Jones, in a note by the colophon on <locus from="329a"
                        to="329a">329a</locus>, states that he received the volume from his friend
                        <persName role="asn" key="person_7537069"
                        ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/7537069">Antoine Polier
                     (1741–1795)</persName>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>After Jones death, his wife <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/3241569" key="person_3241569">Lady Anna Maria
                           Jones (1748–1829)</persName> inherited the volume, then after her death,
                        the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/64237639/" key="person_64237639">R. H. Evans
                           (1778–1857)</persName> sold it on <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1831-05-20">20 May 1831</date> (lot 436), to bookseller <persName
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/69276015/" key="person_69276015"
                           >John George Cochrane (1781–1852)</persName>, who likely acted as an
                        agent on behalf of Chancery Court Clerk and Royal Asiatic Society member
                           <persName role="fmo ato ins" key="person_f3620">Samuel Hawtayne Lewin
                           (1795–1840)</persName>, for whom he evidently also obtained other
                        ex-Jones volumes (e.g. Rylands <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6667"><idno>Persian
                              MS 187</idno></ref> and <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6725">240</ref>;
                        see Lawrence, 'Building a Library', pp. 34, 70, Appendix
                     3).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Lewin's death, his family evidently sold his manuscripts,
                        largely then obtained by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for his library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735"
                           >Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>, paid in two
                        instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901"
                           >1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           type="corporation" role="rps" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John
                           Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
